postcontent: Another rare firearm from my fathers collection, when he passed I had no idea the collection he left behind for his grandchildren. He was a retired military and law enforcement and he loved rare firearms what ever he could find he collected. This is a rare ps90 only a small amount were made this was the first production of the gen 3 they wanted it to look different and standout but they discontinued the entire receiver due to it was to expensive to make compared to the standard versions you see earlier and today as you can see in the pictue. it's all one piece with a low profile eye of sight for any optic, (optics included) it's ingenuity at its best. Has the gen3 trigger pack these are not the gen 4 triggers with after market parts to make a gen 3 as seen online this is the real deal all genuine fn parts. This makes this firearm rarer than rare very hard to find gen3, you won't find them in this configuration not your usual ps90. This looks to be new I am not sure still in factory plastic when retrieved from his war room as you can see in the photo no usage marks where they should be. this comes with a fifty round magazine.

title: For Sale:  Czech Small Arms Sa vz. 61 Pistol, 9mm,  2 mags
postcontent: Czech Small Arms Sa vz. 61 Pistol is the semi-automatic version of the legendary Sa vz. 61 submachine gun (machine pistol) designed in the late 1950´s in Czechoslovakia. The Sa vz. 61 was designed for reconnaissance units, tank crews, Special Forces, and for security forces of the Ministry of Interior. The Sa vz. 61 was developed to fulfill a specific need: a firearm that could be worn like a pistol (in a holster) and capable of full automatic fire. The design of the Sa vz. 61 was unique in its time. It uses the following common operational features found on a submachine gun: an unlocked bolt, magazine inserted into the bottom of the receiver (outside of the pistol grip) and a folding stock. These common features are combined with the following characteristics not usually found in submachine guns: extraordinary small size, fires from a closed bolt, and uses a rate reducer to slow full automatic fire. The Sa vz. 61 offered by CzechPoint is the semi-automatic version of the original military issued firearm - it is as close as one can get to owning the legendary vz. 61 submachine gun. Except for removal of the full-auto parts and rate reducer, and three modified parts with new safety, this firearm is like those used by Military and Paramilitary units in nearly 20 countries around the world.  As shown in the photo, the Sa vz. 61 finish is comprised of a blued lower receiver with a black paint upper receiver (paint cured at 300 degrees fahrenheit).
